@node SIMPREFS "Running SimPrefs..."

If you have not run Sim4004 before, run SimPrefs first to set up the
configuration. This is not necessary, but advisable. Even if you forget, you
can always run it from within Sim4004 at any time.

@{b}SimPrefs
========@{ub}
The following gadgets are available within the SimPrefs program to configure
the Sim4004 program. Please note that the actual ROMs are configured within
Sim4004 and some things are automatically saved when Sim4004 is exited. These
descriptions are ordered from left to right, top to bottom, as you see on the
window.

 @{b}Use Workbench?@{ub}
     If selected, Sim4004 will run on the Workbench screen, otherwise it
     will open the screen selected in the Screen Selection gadget.

 @{b}Skip User Confirmation@{ub}
     If selected, confirmation requesters will not be displayed. For
     example, "Are you sure you want to Quit?" will not be asked when you
     close the Command Centre window. It will simply terminate the program.

 @{b}Screen Selection@{ub}
     This allows you to set up a Public Screen for your program to use. For
     a description of Public Screens, please see the Workbench manual.
     When the "Use Workbench?" checkbox gadget is selected, this gadget will
     not be enabled, so first disable the "Use Workbench?" checkbox gadget.
     
     The gadget is set up as two parts. The left part is a picture of a
     monitor. Click this to select the screen mode that you want. The right
     part displays the name of the screen mode that you have selected and
     this is what will be used when you the "Use Workbench?" option is not
     selected.
     
     As you can see from the above description, it is a standard screen
     selection gadget. If you know how to use one, you best skip this
     paragraph.
     Click the monitor button on the left part of the screen    selection
     gadget to bring up the Screen Mode Requester.
     Select the name of the screen that you want from the list, and also use
     the colors(sic) slider to select the number of colours required for
     this screen. You are advised to select at least 32 colours, but as with
     most things these days, it looks best with 256 colours or more. Also,
     try to select 800x600 at least. You can get away with 640x400, but the
     registers window may have some trouble fitting. I thought about
     changing the layout of the registers window to accommodate, but figured
     that we are supposed to be moving the Amiga on to later hardware, so
     the more incentive the better. If it really annoys you, let me know and
     I'll consider changing it.
     Once you have selected the screen mode you want, press the "OK" button,
     otherwise press "Cancel" to go back to the original selection.
     
 @{b}RAM Chips Enabled@{ub}
     This is a group of 16 checkbox gadgets. Each enables (or disables) one
     of the RAM Chips. In an MCS-4 system, there can be up to 4 blocks of 4
     RAM chips. Each RAM chip contains 4 registers of 8 bytes (or 16
     nybbles), plus 4 status nybbles per register.
     
     Normally, you would have all of these selected, but you may want to
     configure your system to have less RAM available. The RAM is configured
     as shown below:
     
     A nybble is 4 bits.
     
     Each RAM Register contains 20 nybbles. 16 nybbles of RAM and 4 status
     characters. (10 bytes).
     
     Each RAM Chip contains 4 registers (40 bytes).
     
     Each Block contains 4 RAM Chips (160 bytes).
     
     There are 4 blocks of RAM chips (640 bytes in total).

    Basically, according to the above calculations, each RAM chip you
    disable removes 40 bytes of RAM.

 @{b}Clear All ROMs@{ub}
     This button clears all previously allocated ROM images. This
     functionality will be moved to the ROM Load requester in future
     versions.
 
 
 Once you have set up your environment using SimPrefs, close SimPrefs and run
 Sim4004. From within Sim4004, select 'Open...' from the 'Project' menu. This
 will bring up the 'Load ROM files' requester.
 
 The 'Load ROM files' requester allows you to configure your ROM images as you
 need. Check the supplied program to see which images are to be loaded into the
 available ROM sockets.
 The mechanism for loading the ROM files is the same as that in the Screen
 Selection gadget above. Simply click the file image for each ROM file and use
 the standard file selection requester to select the ROM file you need. They
 will normally have a .bin extension.
 
 Once you have loaded all the ROMs you want, click the 'Done' button.
 
 Sim4004 is now ready for use.
 
@endnode

@node SIM4004  "Running Sim4004..."

When you run Sim4004, you may be presented with a screen selection requester.
This will appear if you have not used SimPrefs to request the Workbench screen
or a selected Public screen. If it does appear, select the screen you would
like to open Sim4004 on. This usually only happens if the preferences are
unavailable or unreadable (as when the program is first started).


@{b}Simulator Command Centre Window
========= ======= ====== ======@{ub}
You are now presented with the Simulator Command Centre window. This window is
the main control panel for the simulation and contains the following buttons
(from left to right):

@{b}GADGETS@{ub}

 @{b}Run@{ub}
     This button starts the MCS-4 simulator running from the current program
     counter (PC). This can also be performed via ARexx.
     
 @{b}Stop@{ub}
     This button will halt a currently running MCS-4 program. The Program
     Counter (PC) is not reset. This can also be performed using ARexx.
     
 @{b}Single-Step@{ub}
     This button only works when the MCS-4 program is stopped. It allows you
     to run an MCS-4 program instruction by instruction so the results can
     be more easily interpreted by the user. One MCS-4 instruction is
     executed each time this button is pressed. This can also be performed
     using ARexx.
     
 @{b}Reset PC@{ub}
     Resets the i4004 Program Counter (PC) to 0x000. This can also be
     performed by directly changing the value in the Registers window, or
     via ARexx.
     
 @{b}Load@{ub}
     Opens the "Load ROM Files" requester and allows you to set up your ROM
     configuration. You need at least one ROM file to run the simulator.
     All ROM files are 256 bytes in size. 16 of these gives you 4k ROM space
     in total. Not much, but a hell of a lot better than the available RAM.
     This function can also be performed by the "Open..." menu item in the
     "Project" menu, or via ARexx. See the "Load ROM Files Requester"
     section below for details.
     
 @{b}Set PC@{ub}
     Opens the "Go To Address" requester. To set the ROM address (which can
     be anything from 0x000 to 0xFFF), click the String gadget to enter and
     modify the last 3 characters to the HEX address you need. Click "Done"
     when complete. This can also be performed by directly changing the
     value in the registers window, or via ARexx.


@{b}MENUS@{ub}

 @{b}Project
     @{b}Open@{ub}
         Opens the "Load ROM Files" requester and allows you to set up
         your ROM configuration. You need at least one ROM file to run
         the simulator. All ROM files are 256 bytes in size. 16 of these
         gives you 4k ROM space in total. Not much, but a hell of a lot
         better than the available RAM. This function can also be
         performed by the "Load" gadget on the "Simulator Command
         Centre" window, or via ARexx. See the "Load ROM Files
         Requester" section below for details.
         
    @{b}About@{ub}
        Displays information about Sim4004, including version, ARexx
        port (if there is one) and the screen name.
        
       @{b}Quit@{ub}
        Exits the Sim4004 program. Can also be performed by closing the
        "Simulator Command Centre" window, Arexx, or Ctrl-C.
        
 @{b}Windows@{ub}
       @{b}Registers@{ub}
           Opens the "Registers" window. See "Registers Window" section
           for details. Closes the window if it is already open.
           
       @{b}Program Listing@{ub}
           Opens the "Program Listing" window. See "Program Listing
           Window" section for details. Closes the window if it is already
           open.
           
       @{b}View ROMs@{ub}
           Opens the "i4001 ROM Viewer" window. See the "ROM Viewer
           Window" section for details. Closes the window if it is already
           open.
           
       @{b}View/Edit RAM@{ub}
        Opens the "i4002 RAM Editor" window. See the "RAM Editor
        Window" section for details. Closes the window if it is already
        open.
        
 @{b}Settings@{ub}
    @{b}Create Icons?@{ub}
        If enabled, an icon is also created for any preferences file
        saved. If disabled, no icon is saved.
        
       @{b}Preferences@{ub}
           Starts the SimPrefs application. See the "Preparing the
           Simulator" section for more details.
           
       @{b}Load Settings...@{ub}
           Allows you to select another preferences file for use with this
           session. You can also elect to save this as your permanent
           prefs file.
           
       @{b}Save Settings@{ub}
           Saves preferences. This is actually fairly redundant as the
           preferences are always saved on exit. Supplied for
           completeness.
           
       @{b}Save Settings As ...@{ub}
           Saves preferences to a file of your choice. You can also elect
           to save this as your permanent prefs file.

 @{b}User@{ub}
       @{b}Load Command Shell@{ub}
           Loads the AmigaDOS Shell on Sim4004's screen. Handy if Sim4004
           is not running on Workbench if you do not want to swap screens
           to execute AmigaDOS commands. Yuo do not need to close this
           window to continue using the simulator.
           
       @{b}Run AmigaDOS Command...@{ub}
           Allows you to run a single AmigaDOS command on Sim4004's
           screen. Handy if Sim4004 is not running on Workbench if you do
           not want to swap screens to execute an AmigaDOS command.
           
           A "Select command..." requester is opened. You can either type
           the command into the string gadget directly, or use the file
           requester (top right gadget that looks like a file) to select
           the command you need. Press the "Done" button to execute. If
           nothing is selected, you will not get an error.
           
       @{b}Run ARexx Script...@{ub}
           Allows you to run a single ARexx script on Sim4004's screen.
           
           A "Select ARexx command..." requester is opened. You can either
           type the command into the string gadget directly, or use the
           file requester (top right gadget that looks like a file) to
           select the script you need. Press the "Done" button to execute.
           If nothing is selected, you will not get an error.
           

@{b}Registers Window
========= ======@{ub}
The Registers window is for displaying and manipulating the i4004 flip flops
and registers. The only registers that cannot be modified are the Stack
registers. These can only be modified by MCS-4 programs. The full menu is also
available from this window. Each of the gadgets and display areas are described
below, as seen from left to right, top to bottom:

 @{b}Flip Flops Group@{ub}
     @{b}Test Flag@{ub}
         MCS-4 programs can check for the status of the Test flag, but
         it can only be set by an external interface, by setting this
         gadget or via ARexx. The meaning of this flag is application
         specific.
         
     @{b}Carry Flag@{ub}
         The Carry flag is set if there is an arithmetic carry or
         after an addition or subtraction operation respectively. It can
         be set and tested by an MCS-4 program and is usually used in
         determining conditional branches. It can also be modified using
         this gadget or via ARexx.
         
 @{b}General Purpose Regs Group@{ub}
     @{b}Accumulator@{ub}
         This is the general purpose accumulator register, usually used
         by MCS-4 applications for arithmetic. It can be modified by
         MCS-4 programs, this gadget, and ARexx. It will accept any
         value from 0x0 to 0xF (a 4-bit value).
 
 @{b}Scratch Registers Group@{ub}
     The i4004 has 16 4-bit scratch registers, organised as 8 pairs. As the
     name suggests, these are general purpose registers that are used to
     store temporary values. As mentioned, they can be addressed by MCS-4
     programs as 16 individual 4-bit registers, or 8 8-bit registers. They
     can be modified by MCS-4 programs, the 16 string gadgets in the Scratch
     Registers Group, or ARexx. Each of the 16 string gadgets accepts values
     from 0x0 to 0xF. The same as the accumulator.
     
 @{b}Pointer Registers Group@{ub}
     @{b}Program Counter@{ub}
         The Program Counter (PC) is a 12-bit address pointing to the
         current instruction being executed. This 12-bit value
         represents 4 kilobytes of address space and refers to ROM ONLY.
         All RAM is addressed using a completely different mechanism
         requiring the RAM/ROM Pointer described below. The PC can be
         modified by MCS-4 programs, this string gadget, ARexx, and the
         "Reset PC" and "Set PC" gadgets of the "Simulator Command
         Centre" window. It can be any hex value from 0x000 to 0xFFF.
         
     @{b}RAM/ROM Pointer@{ub}
         The RAM/ROM pointer doesn't really exist in one position within
         an MCS-4 environment, however, some instructions refer to it as
         a single entity and I have found it best to represent it as
         such. MCS-4 programs should have no problem with it being
         represented as such as the opcode logic within Sim4004 and
         cSim4004 take care of any translations. This also means that
         you can set it via this gadget if you know exactly what you
         are trying to represent, and which bits affect which chips.
         
         Basically, it is used to determine the selected chip (be that
         ROM or RAM) and also the selected register/port etc within the
         required chip. This is a 16-bit register that is defined as
         shown below:
         
             * Bits 15-12 - Selected ROM chip. This is usually a
                            mirror of bits 11-8. If not, some MCS-4
                            programs could get upset. It is
                            separated to view ROM and RAM a bit more
                            separately.
             
             * Bits 11-8  - Selected RAM chip.
             * Bits 7-6   - RAM Register selection.
             * Bits 5-4   - RAM Status byte selection.
             * Bits 3-0   - RAM address (within the register).
         
         This register can be modified by MCS-4 programs, this string
         gadget and ARexx.
             
 @{b}Stack Group@{ub}
    Shows the current status of the 3-level stack. The stack is only ever
    used for 12-bit ROM addresses and is contained entirely within the
    i4004. If more than three addresses are pushed onto the stack, the
    oldest is lost forever, so an MCS-4 program needs to keep an eye on
    this. These values can only be modified my MCS-4 programs.
    

@{b}Program Listing Window
======= ======= ======@{ub}
The Program Listing Window displays the disassembled output of the ROM chips,
from 0x000 to 0xFFF. The highlighted instruction is the one to be executed
next.

The window can be sized vertically, but not horizontally in order to show more
instructions. There is also a scrollbar for scrolling through the ROM chips.

The following keyboard shortcuts are also available:

    0          - View from address 0x000
    1          - View from address 0x100.
    2          - View from address 0x200.
    3          - View from address 0x300.
    4          - View from address 0x400.
    5          - View from addrsss 0x500.
    6          - View from address 0x600.
    7          - View from address 0x700.
    8          - View from address 0x800.
    9          - View from address 0x900.
    a          - View from address 0xA00.
    b          - View from address 0xB00.
    c          - View from address 0xC00.
    d          - View from address 0xD00.
    e          - View from address 0xE00.
    f          - View from addrsss 0xF00.
    
    Esc        - Close the window (valid for all sub-windows).

    Keypad 7   - View from address 0x000.
    Keypad 1   - View end of ROM space.
    Keypad 8   - Scroll up one instruction.
    Keypad 2   - Scroll down one instruction.
    Keypad 9   - Scroll up one window's worth.
    Keypad 3   - Scroll down one window's worth.

    Space      - Scroll down one window's worth.
    Backspace  - Scroll up one window's worth.
    Down Arrow - Scroll down one instruction.
    Up Arrow   - Scroll up one instruction.


@{b}i4001 ROM Viewer Window
===== === ====== ======@{ub}
The ROM Viewer window provides a HEX dump of each of the ROMs individually.

The left hand side of the window contains two gadgets.
At the top is the ROM selection cycle gadget. Use this to choose the ROM chip
you want to view.
At the bottom is the Port string gadget. It allows you to edit the contents of
the ROM Port belonging to the currently selected ROM chip.

The right hand side contains a HEX dump of the ROM contents in the usual HEX
dump format. Basically, it is the address of the first byte, 16 bytes of ROM
displayed as HEX codes, and then those same 16 bytes viewed as ASCII.


@{b}i4002 RAM Editor Window
===== === ====== ======@{ub}
The RAM Editor window allows you to view and edit the various RAM chips that
are available on your system. You can view the window as two halves (left and
right).

The left hand side basically determines what will be displayed on the right.
At the top left is the Block cycle gadget. This is used to select one of four
blocks of four RAM chips.
Below that is the Chip cycle gadget. This is to used to select the actual RAM
chip to view within the selected block. This is also a value from 1 to 4.
The Port string gadget below shows the value of the selected RAM chip's I/O
port.

The right hand side shows the contents of the selected RAM chip. Each chip
contains 4 registers. Each of the 4 registers contains 16 nybbles of RAM and
4 status registers. Each group of 4 status registers is selected by the Status
cycle gadget to the right of each Register string gadget. The value of the
currently selected status register is in the string gadget to the right of
each cycle gadget.

To manipulate any of the registers, status nybbles or ports directly, select
the required block, RAM chip and, if required, status port. Click within the
string gadget you want to alter and type in the new values. Each of the string
gadgets is activated in overwrite mode instead of insert mode, so old values
need not be deleted.


@{b}Load ROM Files Requester
==== === ===== =========@{ub}
The Load ROM Files requester appears if you select the 'Open' menu item from
the 'Project' menu, or click the 'Load' button on the Simulator Command Centre
window. This window can be resized as normal.

This requester is designed to enable the configuration of ROM files on an MCS-4
system. Unfortunately, due to the way MCS-4 works, you need to select each 256
byte ROM chip indicidually and place it in one of the 16 ROM slots (represented
as '4001 ROM 0:' through to '4001 ROM F:'. Sixteen of these 256 byte ROMs gives
you a total of 4 kilobytes of ROM, plus 16 output ports.

To select a file, click the file icon next to the ROM slot you want to use to
open a standard file requester. Select the file that you want. The requester
looks for files with a .bin extension by default. You can change this to find
any file name you want, though. See the AmigaOS Workbench manual for
information on how to use the file requester.

Once a file is selected, it will be displayed in the string gadget to the
right of the file icon. This is not editable. You can only change this by
selecting the ROM chip you want. To clear it, you need to select the 'Clear all
ROMs' option in SimPrefs. This clears all ROMs at once. Delete buttons for
individual ROM slots will be added in future.

Once you have selected all the ROM chips you want, press the done button. The
selected files will be remembered after you quit.


@{b}Select Command Requester
====== ======= =========@{ub}
The Select Command Requester is invoked when you select 'Run AmigaDOS
Command...' from the 'User' menu.

It appears in the middle of the screen and consists of three gadgets, a string
gadget that holds the command name, a file selection gadget that allows you to
select the command you want using a File Requester, and the 'Done' gadget which
is either used to execute the required command, or simply exit if no command
was selected.

The string gadget is editable, so you can just type the name of the command
here if you know what you are looking for.

If you need to search for the command, use the file selection gadget to the
right of the string gadget. This will bring up a standard File Requester that
you can use to select the command you want to run. This will open in the C:
directory by default.See the AmigaOS Workbench manual for more information on
how to use the File Requester. The selected command will appear in the string
gadget if one is selected.

Once you have the command you want in the string gadget, press the 'Done'
button to execute it. If the string gadget is empty, 'Done' simply exits the
requester.

All output from the command will appear on the same screen Sim4004 is open on.


@{b}Select ARexx Script Requester
====== ===== ====== =========@{ub}

The Select ARexx Script Requester is invoked when you select 'Run ARexx
Script...' from the 'User' menu.

It appears in the middle of the screen and consists of three gadgets, a string
gadget that holds the script name, a file selection gadget that allows you to
select the script you want using a File Requester, and the 'Done' gadget which
is either used to run the required script, or simply exit if no script was
selected.

The string gadget is editable, so you can just type the name of the script here
if you know what you are looking for.

If you need to search for the script, use the File Selection gadget to the
right of the string gadget. This will bring up a standard File Requester that
you can use to select the script you want to run. This will open in the REXX:
directory by default. See the AmigaOS Workbench manual for more information on
how to use the File Requester. The selected script will appear in the string
gadget if one is selected.

Once you have the script you want in the string gadget, press the 'Done'
button to execute it. If the string gadget is empty, 'Done' simply exits the
requester.

All output from the ARexx script will appear on the same screen Sim4004 is open
on.
@endnode

@node CSIM4004 "Running cSim4004..."
cSim4004 is the same core program as that comprising Sim4004, only it is
simply an engine that runs from the command line and has no graphical output.
Once a program is debugged using Sim4004 and an assembler, you can run them
quietly in the background using this engine.

Once the program is started, some basic information about the program is
displayed and the program immediately loads all ROMs specified by Sim4004 and
runs this program from address 0x000.

The program can be fully controlled via ARexx in exactly the same way that
Sim4004 can and also can be stopped by simply pressing <Ctrl-C>.

The only differences with the ARexx interface are the obvious ones:
    * You cannot run AmigaDOS or ARexx programs with cSim4004
    * The Screen information function returns NULL.

@endnode

@node AREXX    "ARexx Commands..."

@{b}ARexx Command List@{ub}
===== ======= ====
The following ARexx commands are also available. You can use these to create
simulated hardware that can interact with the i4004 simulator. The commands are
shown in all capitals, and the explanation of each is indented. below:

QUIT
   Quit Sim4004
   
GETATTR APPLICATION.VERSION
   Returns simulator version.
   
GETATTR APPLICATION.SCREEN
   Returns screen address of sim4004 screen.
   
GETATTR APPLICATION.AREXX
   Returns ARexx port name.
   
HELP
   Displays this document.
   
CMDSHELL
   Opens a new AmigaDOS shell for use on the same screen as that running
   Sim4004.
   
RX FILE/A
   Executes an ARexx script.
   
DOSCMD CMD/A
   Executes an AmigaDOS command.


APPLICATION.LOADROM ROM/A FILE/A
   Loads contents of FILE into ROM.
   
APPLICATION.LOADPREFS FILE/A
   Loads preferences file
   
APPLICATION.SAVEPREFS
   Saves preferences as FILE.
   
APPLICATION.ADDHARDWARE PORTNUM/A REXXPORT/A
   Allows an external program to receive messages when an i4002/i4001 port is
   modified. Messages that can be received are defined below. These must be
   processed.
   
APPLICATION.REMHARDWARE PORTNUM/A
   Removes association of an Arexx Port with the specified i4002/i4001 port.
   

CMD.RUN
   Runs the i4004 program.
   
CMD.STOP
   Stops the i4004 program.
   
CMD.STEP
   Executes only one i4004 instruction.
   
CMD.RESETPC
   Resets the i4004 program counter (PC)to 0x000.
   
CMD.GOTO ADDR/A
   Sets the i4004 program counter (PC) to value of ADDR.
   

SETATTR REGS.TEST VAL/A
   Sets the Test flipflop on or off.
   
SETATTR REGS.CARRY VAL/A
   Sets the Carry flipflop on or off.
   
SETATTR REGS.ACC VAL/A
   Sets accumulator to VAL.
   
SETATTR REGS.SCRATCH REG/A VAL/A
   Sets scratch register REG to VAL.
   
SETATTR REGS.SCRATCHPAIR PAIR/A VAL/A
   Sets scratch register pair PAIR to VAL
   
SETATTR REGS.RAMROM VAL/A
   Sets the RAM/ROM Register to VAL.
   
GETATTR REGS.TEST
   Returns the value of the Test flipflop
   
GETATTR REGS.CARRY
   Returns the value of the Carry flipflop
   
GETATTR REGS.ACC
   Returns the value of the accumulator.
   
GETATTR REGS.SCRATCH REG/A
   Returns the value of scratch register REG.
   
GETATTR REGS.SCRATCHPAIR PAIR/A
   Returns the value of scratch pair PAIR.
   
GETATTR REGS.RAMROM
   Returns the value of the RAM/ROM register.
   
GETATTR REGS.PC
   Returns the value of the program counter (PC).
   

ROM.WRITEPORT PORT/A VAL/A
   Writes VAL to ROM Port PORT.


RAM.WRITERAM ADDR/A VAL/A
   Writes VAL to RAM address ADDR.
   
RAM.READRAM ADDR/A
   Returns the value of RAM address ADDR.
   
RAM.WRITESTATUS STAT/A
   Writes VAL to RAM status nybble STAT. STAT is the block, chip and register
   combination that contains the status nybble.
   
RAM.READSTATUS STAT/A
   Returns the value of RAM status nybble STAT. STAT is the block, chip and
   register combination that contains the status nybble.
   
RAM.WRITEPORT PORT/A VAL/A
   Writes VAL to RAM Port PORT.
   
RAM.READPORT PORT/A
   Returns the value of RAM Port PORT.


@{b}AREXX COMMANDS THAT HARDWARE SIMULATORS WILL RECEIVE
===== ======== ==== ======== ========== ==== =======@{ub}
ROMPORT PORT/A VAL/A
   Advises you which ROM Port has been modified. The receiving application can
   then request the value.

RAMPORT PORT/A VAL/A
   Advises you which RAM Port has been modified. The PORT parameter is
   represented as B.C, where B is the hex block number (0-F), and C is the chip
   number (0-3). These are separated by a decimal point. The receiving
   application can then request the value.

TESTFLIPFLOP STATUS
   Advises you if the Test flip flop was just switched on or off, as indicated
   by the STATUS parameter, which can be the string value 'OFF' or 'ON'.

The above commands are the only ones your external programs need to process. It
is suggested that you use APPLICATION.ADDHARDWARE to register your ARexx port
with Sim4004 and then only process the messages for the ports you need. Since
the i4002 (RAM) ports are I/O, you can also set those ports via your external
programs. Although the ARexx interface allows you to set other aspects of the
i4004, this functionality really only exists for test scripts, not simulated
hardware.

@{b}***** SEE EXAMPLES DIRECTORY FOR USAGE OF THESE AREXX COMMANDS *****@{ub}

@endnode

@node PROGRAMMING "Programming the Sim4004"

The i4004 programming model consists of the following:

    * 4 Kilobytes of ROM address space as follows:
        * 16 256-bit ROM chips.
        
    * 640 bytes of RAM represented as follows
        * 4 Groups of 4 RAM chips (16 chips)
            * Each RAM chip has 4 Registers.
                * Each register has 8 bytes and 4 status
                  nybbles
    
    * 16 Output Ports (1 per RAM chip)
    
    * 16 I/O Ports (1 per ROM chip)
    
    * Accumulator Register (4-bits wide)
    
    * Program Counter Register (12-bits)
    
    * 16 scratch registers (4-bits wide)
        * The 16 scratch registers can be grouped as 8 (8-bit wide)
          scratch register pairs.
    
    * 3-level stack (3 12-bit registers only used to store addresses)

These are all programmed using the  @{"MCS-4 Instruction Set" link INSTRUCTIONSET}

I compiled my programs using the AS assembler. Currently this is not available
for MacOS or AmigaOS but should be able to be ported fairly easily.

AS also compiles programs for many other processors, not just the 4004. It is
worth checking out in my opinion.

Of course, you can always use a HEX editor if you really want authenticity...

@endnode


@node INSTRUCTIONSET "Intel MCS-4 Instruction Set"

*** NOTE See the 4004 example that comes with the AS assembler and also the
***      example programs in this archive for demonstrations of syntax. It
***      can look a little strange so it is worth a look-see

@{b}OPCODE    NAME    SYNTAX        FUNCTION
======    ====    ======        ========@{ub}
00    NOP    NOP        PC = PC + 1
1c aa    JCM    JCM c,aa    If c is true, PC = aa
2s dd    FIM    FIM Rm,dd    Rm = dd
2t    SRC    SRC Rm        Send Register Control (selects ROM/RAM chips)
3s    FIN    FIN Rm        Rm = value of ROM at address pointed to by
                                     scratch register pair 0.
3t    JIN    JIN Rm        PC = Rm
4a aa    JUN    JUN aaa        PC = aaa
5a aa    JMS    JMS aaa        Stack 2 = Stack 1, Stack 1 = Stack 0,
                                Stack 0 = PC, PC = aaa
6r    INC    INC Rn        Rn = Rn + 1, Set Carry on overflow.
7r aa    ISZ    ISZ Rn aa    Rn = Rn + 1, If Rn != 0 PC = aa,
                                else PC = PC + 1
8r    ADD    ADD Rn        Rn = A + Rn + C. Set Carry on overflow.
9r    SUB    SUB Rn        Rn = A - Rn - C. Set Carry on borrow.
Ar    LD    LD  Rn        A = Rn
Br    XCH    XCH Rn        Swap A with Rn.
Cd    BBL    BBL d        PC = Stack 0, Stack 0 = Stack 1,
                                Stack 1 = Stack 2, Stack 2 = 0x000. A = d
Dd    LDM    LDM d        A = d
E0    WRM    WRM        Write A to previously selected RAM character.
E1    WMP    WMP        Write A to previously selected RAM Output port.
E2    WRR    WRR        Write A to previously selected ROM I/O port.
E3    WPM    WPM        <<<UNSUPPORTED (4008/4009 only)>>>
E4    WR0    WR0        Write A to status character 0 of previously
                selected RAM port.
E5    WR1    WR1        Write A to status character 1 of previously
                selected RAM port.
E6    WR2    WR2        Write A to status character 2 of previously
                selected RAM port.
E7    WR3    WR3        Write A to status character 3 of previously
                selected RAM port.
E8    SBM    SBM        Subtract previously deleted RAM character from
                A with borrow. Set carry on borrow.
E9    RDM    RDM        A = previously selected RAM character.
EA    RDR    RDR        Read IO port of previously selected ROM chip.
EB    ADM    ADM        A = A + previously selected RAM character. Set
                Carry on overflow.
EC    RD0    RD0        A = status character 0 of previously
                selected RAM port.
ED    RD1    RD1        A = status character 1 of previously
                selected RAM port.
EE    RD2    RD2        A = status character 2 of previously
                selected RAM port.
EF    RD3    RD3        A = status character 3 of previously
                selected RAM port.
F0    CLB    CLB        A = 0, Carry is cleared.
F1    CLC    CLC        Carry is cleared.
F2    IAC    IAC        A = A + 1. Set Carry on overflow.
F3    CMC    CMC        Complement Carry.
F4    CMA    CMA        Complement A.
F5    RAL    RAL        Roll contents of A left by 1 bit. LSB of A =
                Carry. Carry = MSB of A.
F6    RAR    RAR        Roll contents of A right by 1 bit. MSB of A =
                Carry. Carry = LSB of A.
F7    TCC    TCC        LSB of A = Carry. Carry is cleared.
F8    DAC    DAC        A = A - 1. Set Carry on borrow.
F9    TCS    TCS        LSB of A = Carry, A = A - 1. Clear Carry.
FA    STC    STC        Set Carry.
FB    DAA    DAA        
FC    KBP    KBP        If A = 0000 then A = 0000. If A = 0001 then A
                = 0001. If A = 0010 then A = 0010. If A = 0100
                then A = 0011. If A = 1000 then A = 0100. If A
                = anything else then A = 1111.
FD    DCL    DCL        Selects the required ROM/RAM chip. A designated
                required chip number.


@{b}LEGEND
======@{ub}
PC  = Program Counter
aa  = 8-bit address.
a   = 4-bit address.
aaa = 12-bit address.
c   = Condition Code. Bit definition:
    0 = Invert Jump Condition (as defined by other bits).
    1 = Accumulator equals zero.
    2 = Carry is set.
    3 = Test Signal is clear.
s   = Scratch Register Pair, followed by a binary 0. (Even numbers)
dd  = 8-bit value.
Rm  = Scratch Register Pair.
t   = Scratch Register Pair, followed by a binary 1. (Odd numbers)
r   = Scratch Register.
d   = 4-bit value.
A   = Accumulator Register.
LSB = Least Significant Bit.
MSB = Most Significant Bit.


@{b}NOTES
=====@{ub}
SRC selectss the address and RAM block/chip for the I/O instructions.

KBP converts the accumulator contents from a 1-out-of-4 code to a 1-bit binary
code.

@endnode